04270nam a22006615i 9780226576718DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265767187 a10.7208/97802265767182doi  a(DE-B1597)521328  a(OCoLC)1061503067  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ1090.3b.I27 2019 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a155.33209732231 aIbson, John, eauthor.14aThe Mourning After :bLoss and Longing among Midcentury American Men /cJohn Ibson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b35 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: Sexual Identity on the Postwar Home Front: Denial's Allure in a Repressive Era -- t1. Putting Space between Men: Male Relationships in Everyday Photography at Midcentury -- t2. War as a Cultural Timeout: The Gallery and Shifting Boundaries of Male Belonging -- t3. Back to Normal: Cultural Work in the Erasure of John Horne Burns -- t4. What It Took: Gore Vidal and the High Price of Midcentury Manliness -- t5. Mourning the Loss: The "Great Sullenness" and the Contours of American Manhood -- tCoda: Bookend for an Era -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn the battlefields of World War II, with their fellow soldiers as the only shield between life and death, a generation of American men found themselves connecting with each other in new and profound ways. Back home after the war, however, these intimacies faced both scorn and vicious homophobia. The Mourning After makes sense of this cruel irony, telling the story of the unmeasured toll exacted upon generations of male friendships. John Ibson draws evidence from the contrasting views of male closeness depicted in WWII-era fiction by Gore Vidal and John Horne Burns, as well as from such wide-ranging sources as psychiatry texts, child development books, the memoirs of veterans' children, and a slew of vernacular snapshots of happy male couples. In this sweeping reinterpretation of the postwar years, Ibson argues that a prolonged mourning for tenderness lost lay at the core of midcentury American masculinity, leaving far too many men with an unspoken ache that continued long after the fighting stopped, forever damaging their relationships with their wives, their children, and each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHomophobiazUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMale friendshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMasculinityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMenzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aGore Vidal. 4aJohn Horne Burns. 4aeveryday photography. 4ahomophobia. 4aintimacy. 4amasculinity. 4amen's relationships. 4amidcentury America. 4amourning. 4apostwar America. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226576718423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226576718.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles